    },
    {
      "id": "r6MWV3i34xEI151260A_B",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 2395.3367344942253,
      "y": 944.6369406869918,
      "width": 1533.5989990234375,
      "height": 250,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 1,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b0M",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 922125731,
      "version": 1022,
      "versionNonce": 1546106221,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1775920823673,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Handle Popular Searches:\n    Way1:\n        - AWS Opensearch Elastic Search have something called \"Node Query Caching\"\n        - It caches the top 10 queries \n    Way2:\n        - We must be using CDN for static File Delivery !\n        - we can cache some of APIs here for short time -> It helps if some hot popular event is getting seached more often.\n        Cons:\n            - It becomes diffcult if your seach works on too much search items like terms, location, venu --> Cannot cache all permutation of the APIs in CDN.\n            - If the location is lat/long --> then definetly there is no point of CDN Caching as it is precise to a particualr location.",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Handle Popular Searches:\n    Way1:\n        - AWS Opensearch Elastic Search have something called \"Node Query Caching\"\n        - It caches the top 10 queries \n    Way2:\n        - We must be using CDN for static File Delivery !\n        - we can cache some of APIs here for short time -> It helps if some hot popular event is getting seached more often.\n        Cons:\n            - It becomes diffcult if your seach works on too much search items like terms, location, venu --> Cannot cache all permutation of the APIs in CDN.\n            - If the location is lat/long --> then definetly there is no point of CDN Caching as it is precise to a particualr location.",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "fn36sUwxokG7NN9aKSCi3",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -1022.3770678797524,
      "y": 996.5599623214123,
      "width": 1251.19921875,
      "height": 450,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 1,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b0N",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1220497379,
      "version": 1507,
      "versionNonce": 2146602189,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1775922170408,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Real Time Update Client about Ticket Status\n\nWhy ?\n    - In Popular events, Seats gets booked very fast, S0, we make API calls\n       but that might take some time --> Client sees stale seat status.\n- Any time a ticket is booked or reserved --> Update the client that ticket is booked.\n\nSol:\n    1. Long polling using while loop in Code\n         Keep a while loop open --> Client sends an HTTP and that is kept open for 30s to 1 min\n         so the server can respond.\n         Super cheap -> No additional infra needed.  Especically if user stays on this page for short time for 5mins.\n    \n    2.  SSE (SEver Sent Events ) between API Gateway - Event CRUD Service - Client\n        It is a persistent connection between server to client, so that server can send info to client.\n        It is a uni-direction connection only from server to client [ Alternatively can use websockets but they are bi-directional ]\n\n-- Implementation is compelx --> Out of Scope for this Design --",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Real Time Update Client about Ticket Status\n\nWhy ?\n    - In Popular events, Seats gets booked very fast, S0, we make API calls\n       but that might take some time --> Client sees stale seat status.\n- Any time a ticket is booked or reserved --> Update the client that ticket is booked.\n\nSol:\n    1. Long polling using while loop in Code\n         Keep a while loop open --> Client sends an HTTP and that is kept open for 30s to 1 min\n         so the server can respond.\n         Super cheap -> No additional infra needed.  Especically if user stays on this page for short time for 5mins.\n    \n    2.  SSE (SEver Sent Events ) between API Gateway - Event CRUD Service - Client\n        It is a persistent connection between server to client, so that server can send info to client.\n        It is a uni-direction connection only from server to client [ Alternatively can use websockets but they are bi-directional ]\n\n-- Implementation is compelx --> Out of Scope for this Design --",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "zhKkmlXb47ONQNXBFlujj",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -1013.2344013809329,
      "y": 1574.6673859221078,
      "width": 916.9393920898438,
      "height": 450,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 1,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b0O",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1856976717,
      "version": 880,
      "versionNonce": 348290317,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1775922124741,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "How to handle super Popular events eg: Taylor Swify Concert\n\nProb:\n    So for few hundered seats, lakhs of people try to book it. To Client,\n    They open the Event and within seconds all seats might get booked. \n    \" Chaos  Event \"\n\nSol:\n    -  Virtual Waiting Queue [ A Chock Point to protect our System ]\n       Very Selectively Introduced based on the event.\n       - They can be put into a wait queue --> User sees a message \n            \"Thanks for booking, You are in a Queue\"\n        \n        Can be a Redis Sorted Set [Priority Queue based on the time when reqs arrives ] \n        \n        Implements a Event driven logic -> Like first 100 seats booked -> let first 100 booking\n        confirms then the next 100 can be allowed.    \n    ",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "How to handle super Popular events eg: Taylor Swify Concert\n\nProb:\n    So for few hundered seats, lakhs of people try to book it. To Client,\n    They open the Event and within seconds all seats might get booked. \n    \" Chaos  Event \"\n\nSol:\n    -  Virtual Waiting Queue [ A Chock Point to protect our System ]\n       Very Selectively Introduced based on the event.\n       - They can be put into a wait queue --> User sees a message \n            \"Thanks for booking, You are in a Queue\"\n        \n        Can be a Redis Sorted Set [Priority Queue based on the time when reqs arrives ] \n        \n        Implements a Event driven logic -> Like first 100 seats booked -> let first 100 booking\n        confirms then the next 100 can be allowed.    \n    ",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
